Regarding the daily death toll, the average number from our models is higher than the official figures, which is expected due to potentially higher underdetection rates and fewer tests being conducted. To further understand this, we analyzed the number of deaths in Colombia from January 1 to April 30, comparing cases between 2019 and 2020; the results are presented in Fig. 5. There is a clear increasing trend after February 26, the day of the first confirmed case of COVID-19 in Colombia, suggesting that the actual death toll could be much higher than reported.

Looking ahead, after the initial phase of the epidemic, we have identified four possible actions that can be taken after 90 days (May 26):
a) Maintain current isolation levels without further action;
b) Lift isolation measures and return to normal activities;
c) Resume only work-related activities with initial network layers and weights restored;
d) Increase isolation by halting remaining work and transport activities.
